<h2>A Brief History of the Dripper</h2>

<p>
  The coffee dripper as we know it traces back to 1908 Germany and <strong>Melitta Bentz</strong>, a Dresden housewife frustrated by the unsanitary nature of cloth filters and the grounds that kept ending up in her cup. She punched a hole in a brass pot and lined it with a page from her son's school notebook — the first paper filter dripper. After filing a patent with the Prussian Imperial Patent Office in 1909, she and her husband Hugo founded Melitta GmbH. Modern pour over coffee begins here.
</p>

<p>
  In 2005, Japan's Hario company released the <strong>V60</strong> and changed specialty coffee forever. Its 60-degree cone, single large drainage hole, and spiral ribs gave skilled baristas unprecedented control over extraction. It became the defining tool of the third wave coffee movement.
</p>

<p>
  The <strong>Chemex</strong> predates both — invented in 1941 by American chemist Peter Schlumbohm, it combines a brewing vessel and carafe in an elegant hourglass shape. Selected by MoMA as an icon of industrial design, Chemex remains in production and in use worldwide more than eight decades later.
</p>

<h2>Three Fundamental Shapes</h2>

<h3>Cone (V-Shape)</h3>
<p>
  Coffee grounds converge toward the center. Water flows through the deepest point of the bed, and the drainage hole is large — placing maximum control in the brewer's hands. Flow rate is largely governed by pour technique. Representative models: Hario V60, Origami Dripper.
</p>

<h3>Trapezoid</h3>
<p>
  Wider at the top, flat or wedge-shaped at the bottom. Grounds spread more evenly, and the smaller drainage hole(s) naturally slow the flow rate, making it more forgiving than cone drippers. Representative models: Melitta (1 hole), vintage Kalita (3 holes).
</p>

<h3>Flat Bottom</h3>
<p>
  Flat base allows grounds to form an even, uniform layer. Typically paired with wave-shaped filters that minimize contact between filter and dripper walls, reducing heat loss and improving flow uniformity. High reproducibility. Representative models: Kalita Wave, Fellow Stagg [X].
</p>

