<h2>Dripper Deep Dives</h2>

<h3>Hario V60</h3>
<p>
  The V60's steep 60-degree cone and single large hole mean the flow rate is almost entirely controlled by the brewer's pour technique — making it both the hardest dripper to master and the one with the greatest expressive ceiling. The spiral ribs prevent filter-wall suction and maintain airflow channels. Ceramic versions retain heat best; plastic versions are unbeatable for travel. A huge proportion of World Barista Championship competitors use the V60.
</p>

<h3>Kalita Wave</h3>
<p>
  Three small holes create a naturally restricted, even flow. The wave filter sits above the flat base on raised ridges, minimizing filter-wall contact and reducing heat loss. The uniform flat bed distributes extraction evenly across all grounds simultaneously. Widely considered more forgiving than V60 while still producing an excellent specialty cup. A staple of high-volume specialty cafés for its consistency.
</p>

<h3>Chemex</h3>
<p>
  The Chemex uses a bonded paper filter three times as thick as standard coffee filters, which removes virtually all coffee oils and colloids. The result is an exceptionally <strong>clean, bright, transparent cup</strong>. The thick filter means flow rate is slow — a full brew can take 4–6 minutes — but the resulting clarity showcases fruity, floral notes in light roast coffees beautifully. Its glass carafe design is elegant enough for the dinner table.
</p>

<h3>Origami Dripper</h3>
<p>
  Developed by Nagoya's Trunk Coffee in 2019, the Origami accepts both V60 cone filters and Kalita wave filters, allowing the brewer to substantially change cup character just by switching filter types. With a cone filter it behaves like a V60; with a wave filter it behaves more like a Kalita. Available in multiple colors of porcelain. Used in international competitions including the WBC.
</p>

<h3>Hario Switch</h3>
<p>
  A V60 body fitted with a silicone valve at the base. Close the valve for full immersion brewing (identical in principle to the Clever Dripper); open it and it drains as a standard V60. Recipes can combine both modes — for example, immerse for 30 seconds with the valve closed, then open the valve and add more water to finish with percolation-style extraction. Versatile and relatively easy to use.
</p>

